{
  "What is the basic principle behind distillation?": "",
  "Separating substances based on differences in their magnetic properties": "",
  "Separating substances based on differences in their boiling points": "",
  "Separating substances based on differences in their particle sizes": "",
  "Separating substances based on differences in their color shading": "",
  "Distillation separates mixtures by heating them so that the substance with the lower boiling point evaporates first, then condensing the vapor back into a purified liquid.": "",
  "What two processes are combined in distillation?": "",
  "Filtration and magnetism": "",
  "Evaporation and condensation": "",
  "Freezing and sublimation": "",
  "Dissolving and crystallization": "",
  "Distillation combines evaporation (turning liquid to vapor by heating) and condensation (cooling vapor back to liquid). This allows you to collect a purified liquid.": "",
  "In simple distillation, what happens to the substance with the lower boiling point?": "",
  "It remains in the flask as a liquid the entire time": "",
  "It evaporates first and is collected as the distillate": "",
  "It sinks to the bottom of the flask as a solid residue": "",
  "It reacts chemically with the other substance and is lost": "",
  "The substance with the lower boiling point evaporates first when the mixture is heated. The vapor then passes through a condenser and is collected as a purified liquid called the distillate.": "",
  "What is the purpose of the condenser in a distillation setup?": "",
  "To heat the mixture until it begins to boil and produce vapor": "",
  "To cool the vapor back into a liquid for collection in a flask": "",
  "To filter out solid impurities from the liquid before heating": "",
  "To measure the temperature of the vapor leaving the flask": "",
  "The condenser cools the hot vapor so it changes back into a liquid (condensation). It typically uses cold water flowing around the tube to absorb heat from the vapor.": "",
  "What is the liquid collected at the end of a distillation process called?": "",
  "The residue": "",
  "The filtrate": "",
  "The distillate": "",
  "The solvent": "",
  "The purified liquid collected after distillation is called the distillate. It is the substance that evaporated first and was then condensed back into liquid form.": "",
  "Can distillation be used to purify drinking water from saltwater?": "",
  "No, salt and water cannot be separated by any method available": "",
  "Yes, the water evaporates and the salt stays behind in the flask": "",
  "No, distillation only works with mixtures of two liquid substances": "",
  "Yes, but only if the salt concentration is below one percent total": "",
  "Distillation can separate water from salt. Water evaporates at 100 degrees C while salt remains in the flask. The water vapor is condensed and collected as pure drinking water.": "",
  "Why is a thermometer placed at the top of the distillation flask?": "",
  "To measure the temperature of the liquid still in the flask": "",
  "To monitor the temperature of the vapor being produced": "",
  "To control the heating element and turn it off if needed": "",
  "To measure the room temperature during the experiment": "",
  "The thermometer monitors the vapor temperature, which tells you which substance is currently evaporating. When the temperature changes, it signals that a different substance is beginning to boil.": "",
  "What is fractional distillation used for?": "",
  "Separating substances that have very different boiling points": "",
  "Separating substances that have very similar boiling points": "",
  "Separating solid substances from liquid substances in a mix": "",
  "Combining multiple pure liquids into a single uniform mixture": "",
  "Fractional distillation uses a fractionating column to separate liquids with similar boiling points more effectively. The column provides multiple evaporation-condensation cycles.": "",
  "Which industry uses fractional distillation on a large scale to separate crude oil?": "",
  "The food and dairy industry": "",
  "The petroleum and oil industry": "",
  "The textile and clothing industry": "",
  "The paper and printing industry": "",
  "The petroleum industry uses fractional distillation to separate crude oil into its many components — gasoline, diesel, kerosene, and other products — based on their different boiling points.": "",
  "After distilling saltwater, what remains in the original flask?": "",
  "Pure water only": "",
  "Nothing at all": "",
  "Solid salt only": "",
  "A new compound": "",
  "When saltwater is distilled, the water evaporates and is collected as the distillate, leaving behind solid salt in the original flask.": "",
  "What is distillation?": "",
  "A process that separates a mixture by evaporating and then condensing components based on their boiling points": "",
  "A process that separates a mixture by passing it through a paper filter to trap any solid particles present": "",
  "A process that separates a mixture by using a magnet to attract the magnetic components out of the mix": "",
  "A process that separates a mixture by dissolving all the components in water and then letting them settle": "",
  "Distillation is a separation technique that heats a mixture to evaporate the component with the lower boiling point, then cools the vapor to condense it back into a purified liquid.": "",
  "What is a 'distillate'?": "",
  "The purified liquid collected after condensation in a distillation process": "",
  "The solid residue that is left behind in the original distillation flask": "",
  "The original mixture that is placed into the flask before heating starts": "",
  "The heat source used to bring the mixture to its boiling point temperature": "",
  "The distillate is the purified liquid that is collected at the end of the distillation process. It is the substance that evaporated and was then condensed back into liquid form.": "",
  "What is a 'condenser' in a distillation setup?": "",
  "A device that heats the mixture to produce vapor for the process": "",
  "A tube that cools vapor back into liquid by removing heat from it": "",
  "A filter that removes solid particles from the vapor as it passes": "",
  "A flask that stores the collected purified liquid after separation": "",
  "A condenser is a tube (often with cold water flowing around it) that cools hot vapor, causing it to condense back into a liquid that can be collected.": "",
  "What does 'boiling point' mean?": "",
  "The temperature at which a liquid changes into a gas throughout the entire liquid": "",
  "The temperature at which a solid melts and becomes a liquid substance instead": "",
  "The highest temperature that any substance can reach before it is destroyed": "",
  "The temperature at which a gas changes directly into a solid without melting": "",
  "The boiling point is the temperature at which a liquid has enough energy for bubbles of vapor to form throughout the liquid, not just at the surface. Water boils at 100 degrees C at standard pressure.": "",
  "What is 'fractional distillation'?": "",
  "A distillation method using a fractionating column to better separate liquids with close boiling points": "",
  "A distillation method that only separates a fraction of the mixture and leaves the rest combined": "",
  "A distillation method that uses freezing instead of heating to separate mixture components apart": "",
  "A distillation method that works only on mixtures containing exactly two different substances total": "",
  "Fractional distillation uses a fractionating column that provides multiple condensation-evaporation cycles. This gives much better separation of liquids with similar boiling points.": "",
  "What does 'condensation' mean?": "",
  "The process of heating a liquid until it turns into gas or vapor": "",
  "The process of cooling a gas or vapor until it becomes a liquid": "",
  "The process of dissolving a solid into a liquid to make a solution": "",
  "The process of filtering solid particles out of a liquid mixture": "",
  "Condensation is the phase change from gas to liquid. In distillation, hot vapor passes through a condenser where it cools and condenses back into a liquid.": "",
  "What does 'evaporation' mean?": "",
  "The process where a liquid turns into gas at any temperature at its surface": "",
  "The process where a gas turns back into a liquid when it is cooled down": "",
  "The process where a solid dissolves completely into a liquid solution now": "",
  "The process where a solid changes directly into a gas without any liquid": "",
  "Evaporation is the process where molecules at the surface of a liquid gain enough energy to escape as gas. Unlike boiling, evaporation can happen at any temperature.": "",
  "What does 'volatile' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "Likely to evaporate easily at relatively low temperatures": "",
  "Likely to explode violently when exposed to a heat source": "",
  "Unable to dissolve in any solvent at any temperature at all": "",
  "Able to change color when exposed to direct bright sunlight": "",
  "A volatile substance evaporates easily because it has a low boiling point and high vapor pressure. In distillation, more volatile substances evaporate first.": "",
  "What is 'crude oil'?": "",
  "A mixture of many different hydrocarbons found naturally underground in the Earth": "",
  "A pure substance made of a single type of hydrocarbon molecule found on the surface": "",
  "A type of vegetable oil used for cooking that is extracted from seeds and plant matter": "",
  "A waste product from factories that is released into rivers and streams as pollution": "",
  "Crude oil is a natural mixture of hundreds of different hydrocarbons found underground. Fractional distillation at refineries separates it into useful products like gasoline and diesel.": "",
  "What does 'purification' mean?": "",
  "The process of removing impurities to obtain a purer substance": "",
  "The process of adding substances together to create a mixture": "",
  "The process of heating a substance until it completely evaporates": "",
  "The process of changing a substance from one state to a new one": "",
  "Purification means removing unwanted substances (impurities) from a material to obtain a purer form. Distillation is one of the most effective purification techniques.": "",
  "In a coastal town with limited fresh water, officials consider building a desalination plant. Which technique would this plant use to convert seawater into drinking water?": "",
  "Chromatography to separate the salt molecules from the water molecules": "",
  "Distillation to evaporate the water and leave the salt behind in the boiler": "",
  "Magnetism to attract the dissolved salt particles out of the seawater supply": "",
  "Sieving to filter the salt crystals out of the liquid seawater through a mesh": "",
  "Desalination plants use distillation (or reverse osmosis) to purify seawater. In distillation, seawater is heated to produce steam, which is then condensed into fresh drinking water.": "",
  "A student distills a mixture of alcohol (boiling point 78 degrees C) and water (boiling point 100 degrees C). Which substance will be collected first?": "",
  "Water, because it is more common and makes up most of the mixture": "",
  "Alcohol, because it has the lower boiling point and evaporates first": "",
  "Both will come out together because they are completely miscible in all ratios": "",
  "Neither will be collected because alcohol and water cannot be separated": "",
  "Alcohol has a lower boiling point (78 degrees C) than water (100 degrees C), so it evaporates first. The alcohol vapor is condensed and collected as the first distillate.": "",
  "At an oil refinery, crude oil is heated in a tall fractional distillation tower. Where in the tower would you expect to find gasoline (low boiling point) collected?": "",
  "At the bottom of the tower where temperatures are the highest overall": "",
  "Near the top of the tower where temperatures are the coolest overall": "",
  "In the exact middle of the tower where temperatures are moderate overall": "",
  "Outside the tower in a separate container away from the heating source": "",
  "In a fractional distillation tower, substances with lower boiling points rise as vapor to the cooler upper sections before condensing. Gasoline, with a low boiling point, is collected near the top.": "",
  "A student tries to distill a mixture but notices the thermometer reading keeps changing instead of staying steady. What does this indicate?": "",
  "The thermometer is broken and needs to be replaced with a new working one": "",
